            <section id="why-transition-care-matters">
              <h2>Why transition care matters</h2>
              <p>
                Winter leaves lawns compacted, matted, and unevenly moist. The first warm weeks of
                spring are your best chance to reset turf health before crabgrass and broadleaf weeds
                compete with new growth. A steady transition plan improves root recovery, keeps soil
                oxygen moving, and gives grass a cleaner, greener start.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section id="step-by-step">
              <h3>Spring kickoff checklist</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Clear winter debris:</strong> Remove sticks, matted leaves, and salt-damaged
                  clutter so turf can breathe.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Inspect for compaction:</strong> If puddling lingers or soil feels hard,
                  prioritize aeration before heavy feeding.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Apply early nutrients:</strong> Light spring fertilization supports steady
                  growth without forcing weak top-heavy blades.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Seed thin patches:</strong> Overseed sparse zones once soil temperatures are
                  favorable and moisture is consistent.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Raise mowing height:</strong> Start with a slightly taller cut to reduce
                  stress while roots wake up.
                </li>
              </ol>
            </section>

            <section id="services-that-help">
              <h3>Services on our site that make the biggest spring difference</h3>
              <p>
                The fastest way to avoid a patchy spring is to combine the right services at the right
                time. Here is how key offerings from our service lineup support your lawn transition:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <a href="/services/fall-winter-cleanup"><strong>Fall/Winter Cleanup</strong></a>
                  carries over into early spring by removing leftover leaf litter and debris that can
                  block sunlight and trap moisture on turf.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <a href="/services/fertilization-weed-control"
                    ><strong>Fertilization &amp; Weed Control</strong></a
                  >
                  provides the nutrient base and early weed prevention your grass needs before weeds
                  crowd out new growth.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <a href="/services/aeration-seeding"><strong>Aeration &amp; Seeding</strong></a>
                  relieves compaction, improves water infiltration, and helps seed establish in thin
                  winter-worn areas.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <a href="/services/mowing"><strong>Mowing</strong></a> keeps spring growth even,
                  prevents scalping, and encourages thicker turf when cut on a consistent schedule.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <a href="/services/bed-maintenance"><strong>Bed Maintenance</strong></a> and
                  <a href="/services/mulching"><strong>Mulching</strong></a> reduce weed pressure
                  around lawn edges and help surrounding plants thrive without stealing water and
                  nutrients from turf.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <a href="/services/tree-shrub-care"><strong>Tree &amp; Shrub Care</strong></a>
                  protects canopy structure and improves light/air flow, helping cool-season turf
                  recover in shaded sections.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section id="weekly-rhythm">
              <h3>A simple weekly rhythm for March and April</h3>
              <ul class="list-unstyled">
                <li><i class="fa fa-check text-success"></i> Week 1: cleanup, edging, and drainage checks</li>
                <li><i class="fa fa-check text-success"></i> Week 2: early fertilizer and weed-prevention pass</li>
                <li><i class="fa fa-check text-success"></i> Week 3: aeration/seeding in compacted or thin areas</li>
                <li><i class="fa fa-check text-success"></i> Week 4+: consistent mowing, moisture monitoring, and spot touch-ups</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section id="when-to-call">
              <h3>When to call in the pros</h3>
              <p>
                If your lawn has widespread thinning, heavy weed pressure, standing water, or a mix of
                shade and sun stress, coordinated service visits save time and improve results.
                Professional timing matters in spring because missing one treatment window can delay
                recovery for the rest of the season.
              </p>
            </section>

